Listening to an old broadcast about a certain mountain village here, very isolated, I've posted photos from it, and how the old people there have kept legends about dragons who control the weather (widespread Slavic belief) and occasionally pick "wives" from the human population

The thing is that in that village it goes up to their parents' generation, including an old lady remembering a "dragon" entering the room of a neighbor's newborn and choosing her as a wife, but the villagers managing to expel him with some "herb ritual", leaving the baby crippled

Folklore professors at the local university make a very strong connection with myths characteristic to Dionysos cults, weirdos see how it's the same motives as "UFO encounters", anthropologists see it as an "undeveloped religion" in its first stages, obvious to see the truth.

As "irrefutable proof" of the dragons' historicity, the villagers present certain stones in the foundations of old houses, that are "too heavy for men to carry" (proving Evola saying how Traditional paganism is "positivist", always relying on objective "proof" and not belief)

The construction of these house foundations, according to an architecture expert, bear very strong resemblance to megalithic structures from the Iron Age in other parts of the world, even if they appear to be far more recent and still in use (they have TVs, running water now)

There was a certain song the women sung during harvest, during which was the time the "dragon" tended to come from the sky and swoop one, even if it happened rarely. Also obviously the entity took a "human form" when coming for women, dragon designated its nature, not mere shape
